title: UNOMI-258 Add support for identify() and track() methods in web-tracker
body:
This commits add basic support to make sure that the identify and track methods do something and send back events to Unomi.
This commit does not contain any documentation but it does add an example to the web tracker example page.
You can view the generated events using the event-tail and event-view commands on the server.

Signed-off-by: Serge Huber <shuber@apache.org>

title: UNOMI-225 Support for ElasticSearch 7
body:
In this branch we are working on supporting ElasticSearch 7, which includes the following changes:
- Changing the TransportClient to REST High level client
- Adjust the data model to split it into one index per different item type
- Improve the index prefixing to be systematic
- Adjusting mapping to reflect the changing in data model, each item type must have a mapping

title: Unomi 225 es7
[UNOMI-256] Add device brand and device name to user agent detector
body: The useragent service does a great job of grabbing more information than is currently persisted, and this adds the device name (`iPhone 7`) and device brand (`Apple`) to the session information - useful for measurement and specific targeting needs.

title: UNOMI-250 Refactoring services into seperate Java packages
body:
Right now we have a bit of a mess in our services implementation sub-project. All the service implementations are in the package:
org.apache.unomi.services.services
I propose that we rename this package to:
org.apache.unomi.services.impl
and that each service gets its own sub-package, for example the RulesServiceImpl would be in:
org.apache.unomi.services.impl.rules
This would make it much easier to activate/deactivate logging per service implementation, because currently it is tricky to get logging activated properly unless using configuration by class. Having it by package would be a lot better.
Utility classes such as ThirdPartyService or the clustering event classes would also be moved with the service sub-package they belong to.
In terms of impact this should minimal, only people activating logs should be notified that the class location has changed.

Signed-off-by: Serge Huber <shuber@apache.org>

title: Return Complete Rules via Rule REST Endpoint /cxs/rules
body:
Previously, when listing all Rules as `GET /cxs/rules`, the returned Rule objects were incomplete, modified definitions of a complete Rule object with different (and fewer) keys. Besides not being particularly RESTful, this also made it difficult to inspect specifics around Rules without querying each individually, or building a detailed query using the `matchAllCondition` condition.

This update makes an existing `getAllRules()` method public and part of the `RuleServiceImplementation`, and returns the entire Rule definition as is expected and equivalent to the result of returning a single Rule definition.

(First PR here, please feel free to correct, modify, or let me know of any PR requirements!)

Feature: UNOMI-70 Upgrade to ElasticSearch 5.x
body:
This PR contains the following changes : 
- Upgrade to ElasticSearch 5.0.1
- ElasticSearch is no longer embedded in Unomi but used as an external service
- Upgrade to Apache CXF 3.0.2
- Upgrade to Apache Karaf 3.0.8
- Package Apache Karaf Cellar 3.0.3

All these upgrades were necessary to make ES 5.X work, for example:
- Karaf Cellar is used to replace the Unomi clustering functionality that was built on ElasticSearch and that was relying on the fact that ES was being embedded
- ElasticSearch embedding is no longer supported by Elastic, so we've now moved it out of Apache Unomi and use is as a remote external service just in the same way we would do with a database.
- Mappings had to change because in ES 5.x the type "string" has been replace by two types : "text" and "keyword". As the "text" type doesn't support aggregation we used "keyword" for most of the mappings, and had to add quite a few to make sure everything works correctly. Maybe we also need to improve the dynamic templates to make sure that everything is properly mapped.

There are still some known issues to work out : 
- Some features don't seem to work yet (some loading / saving issues)
- Integration tests and performance tests don't work yet
- Migration path hasn't been tested yet.

title: Feature: UNOMI-28 Upgrade to ElasticSearch 2.x
body:
Moved from pull request #7 to this one because of a branch change to use jgitflow.

Used this resource to perform changes:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/breaking_20_java_api_changes.html

A lot of changes are contained in this commit, notably :

- Moved data directory from KARAF_HOME/data to KARAF_HOME/elasticsearch/data
- Fixes on dates
- Replace all filter classes with query classes as these don't exist in ES 2.x any more
- Replace and/or ES clauses with bool must/should
- Had to replace deleteByQuery support to add plugin by default, since in ES 2.x they externalized the functionality
- Had to install Groovy and Expression modules since they are no longer part of the core

What is NOT done by this patch is the migration procedure
